# Git Workflow Standard (MANDATORY)

## Architecture: Desktop/projects → Production

```
Desktop/projects (DEVELOPMENT)          ~/.pi/agent (PRODUCTION)
─────────────────────────────          ──────────────────────
unified-manager/ ──── push ───→ GitHub ──── pull ───→ unified-manager/
dashboard-tools/ ──── push ───→ GitHub ──── pull ───→ dashboard-tools/
issue-tracker/ ──── push ───→ GitHub ──── pull ───→ issue-tracker/
```

**Desktop/projects** = Source of Truth (develop here)  
**~/.pi/agent** = Production Clones (do NOT edit directly)

## Rules

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| **1. NEVER edit ~/.pi/agent directly** | These are production clones; only `git pull` to update |
| **2. ALWAYS develop in Desktop/projects** | This is the source of truth |
| **3. COMMIT on task completion** | Write meaningful commit messages |
| **4. PUSH after review or batch** | Only push when reviewed or batching multiple reviewed commits |
| **5. PULL to production** | After pushing, update ~/.pi/agent |

## Core Principle: Commit ≠ Push

| Action | Trigger | Meaning |
|--------|---------|---------|
| **Commit** | Task completed | Local save, task is done |
| **Push** | Review passed OR batch ready | Sync to GitHub for backup/production |

### Why Split?

When using unified-manager to orchestrate agents:
- **Commit** = Task marked Done on kanban
- **Push** = After review/validation OR when batching multiple reviewed commits

This allows reviewer agents to validate changes before they go to production.

